Publishing Artifact to Maven Central

Erik Englund
Follow
Apr 2, 2019 · 5 min read

Recently I went about publishing my first artifact to Maven Central. While there are many excellent articles available I found they didn’t exactly work for me out of the box. I’d like to share my experience, where I had problems, and what I learned.

Prior Art

I will skip over several details. This article is meant as a starting point instead of restating what has already been said in other great works.

First off I’d like to thank this article Seun Matt for its excellent help:

  • How to Upload an Open-Source Java Library to Maven Central

Initial Setup

Obviously, we need something to deploy. For me I was uploading the artifacts from for a bunch of maven tiles I’ve made.

efenglu/maven

Be sure to set your pom groupid, artifactid and version. Artifact and version can be anything you want, but groupid should be either a URL domain you control or something like your github organization. Don’t have a Github org? Well, if you are a Github user, Good NEWS! You are an organization.

For me I used:

io.github.efenglu

Pom Project Description

Setup your pom definition to include:

  • name — typically ${project.groupid}:${project.artifactid}
  • description
  • URL — URL to git repository
  • license
  • developers
  • scm
  • distributionManagement — Sonatype

Sonatype Setup

You will need an account on Sonatype. Go to sonatype.org and register for an account.

You will also need to create a project.

Refer to this guide for details: OSSRH GUIDE

This can take a day or two.

GPG Setup

We need to sign all of our artifacts. To do this we will need a GPG key.

gpg --full-generate-key

Don’t forget we need to publish the key to Ubuntu’s keystore.

gpg --keyserver keyserver.ubuntu.com --send-keys ${KEY_ID}

Maven Settings

We need to store all of our credentials outside the pom. We can do this via our settings.xml file.

~/.m2/settings.xml:

You could store them directly in the settings.xml. However, some may not like storing password in plain text. Another alternative is to have settings.xml reference an environment variable that you will set only when you actually do a release.

To have maven reference an environment variable start the variable reference with “env.” followed by the name of the environment variable.

For example:

<gpg.passphrase>${env.GPG_PASSPHRASE}</gpg.passphrase>

Maven Build Plugins

There are several plugin we need to add:

  • javadoc — create a jar containing the javadocs
  • source jar — create a jar contain the source
  • gpg signing plugin — sign all the artifacts with out GPG signature
  • nexus staging plugin — Deploy to nexus staging and release repositories

I put them in a profile so they are only executed during a release.

Release

Now we are ready to actually perform the release.

Choose a new version for the release. It is best to set this to an environment variable as we will be referring to it often:

export newVersion=1.0.0

Set the release version

Set the version of the pom’s to the release artifact version

./mvnw versions:set -DnewVersion=${newVersion} \
   -DgenerateBackupPoms=false

Build and Test

Build and test the release to ensure everything is correct

./mvnw clean install -Prelease

Verify the GPG Signature

Verify the correct signature was used to sign the artifacts

gpg --verify target/*.pom.asc

You should see your email in the results something like this:

gpg: assuming signed data in '***********'
gpg: Signature made Sun Mar 31 22:34:40 2019 CDT
gpg:                using RSA key
**************************
gpg: Good signature from "Erik Englund <*****@gmail.com>" [ultimate]

Deploy the Release

Deploy the release to Sonatype

./mvnw clean deploy -Prelease

Assuming Maven is successful your artifact should be available from Maven Central within an hour or so. Your artifact may not show up in searches ocentral for several hours.

Commit and Tag Release

At this point we are “done” but we should also tag our release on Github.

git add .
git commit -m "Release ${newVersion}"
git tag ${newVersion}
git push --tags

Don’t forget to roll back your changes to they don’t get added to the main codebase:

git reset HEAD~1
git checkout .
git clean -fd

Automate

At this point our release process is manual. Let’s automate it.

With a shell script:

#!/bin/bash -e
DIR="$( cd "$( dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}" )" >/dev/null 2>&1 && pwd )"

export VERSION=$1

if [[ -z "$VERSION" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: Version is undefined"
  exit 1
fi
if [[ -z "${SONATYPE_USERNAME}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: SONATYPE_USERNAME is undefined"
  exit 1
fi
if [[ -z "${SONATYPE_PASSWORD}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: SONATYPE_PASSWORD is undefined"
  exit 1
fi
if [[ -z "${GPG_KEYNAME}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: GPG_KEYNAME is undefined"
  exit 1
fi
if [[ -z "${GPG_PASSPHRASE}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: GPG_PASSPHRASE is undefined"
  exit 1
fi

mvn versions:set -DnewVersion=${VERSION} -DgenerateBackupPoms=false
mvn clean deploy -B -P release --settings ${DIR}/settings.xml
git checkout .
git tag $VERSION
git push tags

Run the script like this:

./release.sh 1.0.2

For a complete example checkout my repository on Github:

efenglu/maven

Example project containing a pom with lots of plugins - efenglu/maven

github.com
